### 1. Create a new employee (Valid)
POST http://localhost:8080/employee
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "title": "Mr.",
  "firstName": "John",
  "lastName": "Smith",
  "middleName": "Alexander",
  "email": "john.smith@example.com",
  "phone": "+79991234567"
}

### 2. Create a duplicate employee (Should return 409 Conflict)
POST http://localhost:8080/employee
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "title": "Mr.",
  "firstName": "John",
  "lastName": "Smith",
  "middleName": "Alexander",
  "email": "john.duplicate@example.com",
  "phone": "+79990000000"
}

### 3. Get employee by ID (Valid)
# Need change {id} to ID which returned at first response
GET http://localhost:8080/employee/1

### 4. Get employee by invalid ID (Should return 404 Not Found)
GET http://localhost:8080/employee/9999

### 5. Create employee with missing fields (Should return 400 Bad Request)
POST http://localhost:8080/employee
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "title": "Mr.",
  "lastName": "Smith"
}

### 6. Create employee with invalid email (Should return 400 Bad Request)
POST http://localhost:8080/employee
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "title": "Mr.",
  "firstName": "John",
  "lastName": "Doe",
  "email": "not-an-email",
  "phone": "+79991234567"
}

### 7. Create employee with invalid phone format (Should return 400 Bad Request)
POST http://localhost:8080/employee
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "title": "Mr.",
  "firstName": "John",
  "lastName": "Doe",
  "email": "john.doe@test.com",
  "phone": "123"
}

### 8. GET request with wrong type (Should return 400 Bad Request)
GET http://localhost:8080/employee/abc